A circular steel shaft [`CDE`] is of length [`2L = [2*$l]`] [`m`] and radius [`r_s=[$as]`] [`mm`] is fixed at [`C`] and free at [`E`]. A circular brass shaft [`AB`] of length [`L = [$l]`] [`m`] and radius [`r_b=[$ab]`] is fixed at A and is kept in parallel with the steel shaft. The end [`B`] of the brass shaft has a gear of radius [`[$bgear]`] [`cm`]. The mid span [`D`] of the steel shaft carries a gear of radius [`[$dgear]`] [`cm`], which is perfectly meshed with the gear of the brass shaft. The shear moduli for the steel and brass shafts are [`G_s=[$gs]`] [`GPa`] and [`G_b=[$gb]`] [`GPa`], respectively.
1. If the allowable shear stress for the steel shaft and the brass shaft are [`\tau_s=[$tauSAllow]`] [`MPa`] and [`\tau_b=[$tauBAllow]`] [`MPa`], respectively, determine the maximum torque [`T_{E_{max}}`], that can be applied at the free end [`E`] of the steel shaft such that the allowable shear stresses are not exceeded in the two-shaft unit.
2.	Determine the angle of rotation of the steel shaft at [`E`] corresponding to this maximum torque. 

[`T_{E_{max}}=`] [____]{"$teMax"} [`kNm`]  
[`\phi=`] [____]{"$phi"}[`^{\circ}`]

